Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, launches a startup to compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
Inrut, the last project of this technology legend, is a Solid-based company, Berners Lee's open source platform.
Solid allows users to choose where to store their data and what people can access what information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee lucky that the intention to hide Inrupt is to "dominate the world."
"We have to do it," he said about the startup.
"This is a historic moment."
The application uses Solid's technology to allow people to create their own online personal data storage or POD.
Contact lists, to-dos lists, calendars, music and other personal and professional tools may be included.
It's like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify were available on a single browser at the same time.
All this makes this personal data store unique is that the user has a complete control over who can access what information.
The company qualifies this as a "personal empowerment through data".
Inrupt's idea, according to his president John Bruce, is that the company provides appropriate resources, processes and skills to help Solid be available to everyone.
The company is currently made up of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security company owned by IBM, some developers hired to work on the project and a community of volunteer developers.
From this week on, developers from around the world could create their own decentralised applications with the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee stated that neither he nor his team spoke to "Facebook nor Google about whether or not to introduce a complete change that would modify his business models from day to day.
